 way to today's celebrity-distribution complex, Bill Fox examines the amount of power accorded to people well-known for being well-known, from Donald Trump to Justin Trudeau. Taking on a Canadian perspective, Fox addresses the disturbing cries of "fake" news in the post-truth age and demonstrates how journalism, no longer the domain of a select few political reporters and editors, has become decentralized and disaggregated.In a world that now plays out on mobile devices, Trump, Trudeau, Tweets, Truth seeks a path through the debris left behind by recent seismic shifts in political media and technology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCommunication in politicsxTechnological innovations. 0aFake newsxPolitical aspects. 0aJournalismxTechnological innovations. 0aMass media and public opinion. 0aOnline journalism. 0aPress and politics. 0aSocial media and journalism. 0aSocial mediaxPolitical aspects. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  acanada.  ademocrat.  adonaldtrump.  aelection.  aliberal.  apoliticalscience.  apolitics.  arepublican.  atrudeau.  ausa.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311127214608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2022z978311127419540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978022800247540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228002475423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228002475/original  a978-3-11-127214-6  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  a978-3-11-127419-5  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles